                .lfoot a{color:var(--muted)}
                .lfoot-links{display:flex;gap:20px;flex-wrap:wrap}
                .lfoot p{display:inline}
                @media(max-width:560px){.lnav-right > a{display:none}}
                
                .code{background:#0B0B0D;border-radius:14px;padding:20px 24px;margin:10px 0 18px;
                    font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:.92rem;line-height:1.7;overflow-x:auto}
                .code .cl{color:#F2F2F4;white-space:pre}
                .kv{display:grid;grid-template-columns:190px 1fr;gap:6px 18px;margin:10px 0 18px}
                .kv .k{color:var(--muted);font-size:.95rem}
                .kv .v{color:var(--ink2);font-size:.95rem}
                @media(max-width:560px){.kv{grid-template-columns:1fr}}

        End
        
        Div class "lnav"
            Div class "lbrand"
                Link "EPL" to "/"
            End
            Div class "lnav-right"
                Link "Docs" to "https://abneeshsingh21.github.io/EPL/"
                Link "Back to site" to "/"
                Div class "lnav-cta-wrap"
                    Link "Install" to "/#install"
                End
            End
        End
        Div class "legal"

            Div class "eyebrow"
                Text "Learn · EPL fundamentals"
            End
            Heading "What is EPL?"
            Div class "updated"
                Text "Last updated 20 July 2026 · applies to EPL v10.2.0"
            End
            Div class "intro"
                Text "EPL — the English Programming Language — is a real, open-source programming language whose syntax reads like plain English. You write statements such as Say, Create, If … Then, and For each, and EPL runs them on a bytecode virtual machine, compiles them to a native executable with LLVM, or transpiles them to Python, JavaScript, Kotlin and more. It installs in one command: pip install eplang."
            End

            Div class "lh2"
                Text "EPL the language, not the football league"
            End
            Text "If you searched for EPL expecting the English Premier League, that is a different EPL — this page is about software. In programming contexts, EPL stands for English Programming Language: a general-purpose language created by Abneesh Singh, distributed on PyPI as eplang, and developed openly on GitHub under the Apache-2.0 license. Its official website is eplang.me."

            Div class "lh2"
                Text "What EPL code looks like"
            End
            Text "Here is a complete, runnable EPL program — no semicolons, no curly braces:"
            Div class "code"
                Div class "cl"
                    Text "Note: greet every user"
                End
                Div class "cl"
                    Text "Create users = [ Ada, Grace, Alan ]"
                End
                Div class "cl"
                    Text "For each name in users"
                End
                Div class "cl"
                    Text "    Say name"
                End
                Div class "cl"
                    Text "End"
                End
            End
            Text "Every block ends with the word End. Conditionals use If … Then … Otherwise. Comments start with Note:. The same source file can be executed directly, compiled, or transpiled — one codebase, many targets."

            Div class "lh2"
                Text "EPL at a glance"
            End
            Div class "kv"
                Div class "k"
                    Text "Paradigm"
                End
                Div class "v"
                    Text "Imperative, with functions, classes, and a declarative web DSL"
                End
                Div class "k"
                    Text "Status"
                End
                Div class "v"
                    Text "Actively developed — current version 10.2.0"
                End
                Div class "k"
                    Text "License"
                End
                Div class "v"
                    Text "Apache-2.0, open source"
                End
                Div class "k"
                    Text "Install"
                End
                Div class "v"
                    Text "pip install eplang (Python 3.9+ on Windows, macOS, Linux)"
                End
                Div class "k"
                    Text "Execution"
                End
                Div class "v"
                    Text "Bytecode VM (default), tree-walking interpreter, LLVM native binaries, WebAssembly"
                End
                Div class "k"
                    Text "Transpiles to"
                End
                Div class "v"
                    Text "Python, JavaScript, Node.js, Kotlin, MicroPython"
                End
                Div class "k"
                    Text "Standard library"
                End
                Div class "v"
                    Text "725+ built-in functions: strings, math, collections, HTTP, SQLite, auth/JWT, files, time"
                End
                Div class "k"
                    Text "Tooling"
                End
                Div class "v"
                    Text "CLI (epl run/build/test/repl), VS Code extension with LSP, package manager, browser playground"
                End
            End

            Div class "lh2"
                Text "How is EPL different from Python?"
            End
            Text "Python is already famous for readability, but it still uses programmer notation — def, elif, ==, f-strings. EPL goes further: keywords are English words and whole statements read as sentences (Create score = 10, If score is greater than 5 then …). Under the hood the trade-offs differ too: EPL ships its own bytecode VM and an LLVM backend for native executables, and it can transpile the same program to several host languages. Python has a vastly larger ecosystem; EPL focuses on approachability without giving up real tooling."

            Div class "lh2"
                Text "Who is EPL for?"
            End
            Text "Students and first-time programmers who want to learn logic without syntax friction. Educators who need code a whole classroom can read aloud. Developers prototyping web APIs, CLI tools, or automations quickly. And AI-assisted workflows — because EPL reads like English, language models generate and review it naturally; the machine-readable reference lives at eplang.me/llms.txt."

            Div class "lh2"
                Text "Is EPL a real programming language?"
            End
            Text "Yes. EPL is a genuine general-purpose language with a lexer, parser, type checker, bytecode VM, LLVM native compiler, test framework, and package manager. It is not a toy or a pseudocode notation — programs run, compile, and ship."

            Div class "lh2"
                Text "Is EPL free?"
            End
            Text "Yes. EPL is open source under the Apache-2.0 license. The compiler, standard library, VS Code extension, and playground are all free."

            Div class "lh2"
                Text "How do I install EPL?"
            End
            Text "Install Python 3.9 or newer, then run pip install eplang. Verify with epl --version, and run your first program with epl run hello.epl. You can also try it without installing anything in the browser playground."

            Div class "lh2"
                Text "What does EPL stand for?"
            End
            Text "In this context, EPL stands for English Programming Language. The acronym is also used by the English Premier League (football) and other fields — those are unrelated to this project."

            Div class "lh2"
                Text "Can EPL build real applications?"
            End
            Text "Yes — web servers and JSON APIs (with routing, SQLite, and auth built in), command-line tools, desktop apps, and native binaries. The eplang.me website itself is written in EPL."

            Div class "box"
                Text "Ready to try it? Install with pip install eplang, or open the playground — no setup required. Questions: contact@eplang.me."
            End

        End
        Div class "lfoot"
            Span class "c"
                Text "© 2024–2026 Abneesh Singh · EPL · Apache-2.0"
            End
            Div class "lfoot-links"
                Link "Home" to "/"
                Link "Terms" to "/terms"
                Link "Privacy" to "/privacy"
                Link "Contact" to "mailto:contact@eplang.me"
            End
        End
    End
End
